    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Part C\n",
        "1. The hedgehog ignores the following variables:\n",
        "\n",
        "- age wages often rise with experience but eventually plateau.\n",
        "variables of year\n",
        "- macroeconomic conditions (inflation, recessions, labor demand).\n",
        "Health\n",
        "- health limitations can affect productivity and hours worked.\n",
        "-Race — structural inequalities may influence opportunities.\n",
        "Marital status — correlated with stability, mobility, and household structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Real-world wage outcomes often depend on interactions, not isolated effects.\n",
        "*   Education x Age - college degree may boost your wage later on in the career rather than early on.\n",
        "*   Education x Job Class A college degree in a \"blue collar\" job may ear less than a high-school gradudate in a high-demand technical job.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*  Race x Education wage to race could vary across demographic groups\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*   Age x health  - older workers with health limitations may earn less despite their experience\n",
        "*   Education x Year - economic cycles could change the wage for premium degrees over time\n",
        "\n",
        "A single-variable model cannot capture these nonlinear, conditional, or synergistic relationships, therefore it is important to consider those as well.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. In this dataset we see noise in the form of:  \n",
        "- Wage variation within the same education level. People with identical education levels earn very different wages.\n",
        "-Outliers in wage. Some individuals earn extremely high wages relative to peers, adding instability to averages and regressions.\n",
        "- Unmeasured variables. The dataset lacks information on:occupation type, industry, geographic region, employer characteristics, skill level all which can create unexplained variation.\n",
        "- Categorical variables with broad buckets, “Some College” or “College Grad” hides huge internal variation, creating noise inside categories.\n",
        "\n",
        "the fox thinking would look at all of these variations rather than one measurement as we did before with the hedgehog."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ZX9u-h-Uvq-Q"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# How to advise\n",
        "When thinking about what career decision and your education you have to take into consideration your skill set, the enjoyment of your career versus the salary you make, and the time you want to invest into your degree. If you choose to further your education there is also a cost associated with that so what is your return on investment for getting an advance degree and what is your productive salary. You need to look at the data without aggergation and within your specific industry and geographical location to determine what is truly the best decision. Do not focus on wage alone."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "YPM854XYwXH2"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Part D**\n",
        "Signal in the wage data shows up in the broad, stable relationships—especially the strong link between education and higher wages and the predictable rise and plateau pattern of wages across age. These trends appear consistently across the dataset and align with well established labor market research, making them reasonably trustworthy even without additional sources. They reflect structural forces rather than random fluctuations, therefore we can treate them as meaningful patterns rather than coincidences.\n",
        "\n",
        "Noise appears in the large wage differences among people with the same education level, the presence of outliers, and the many unmeasured factors—such as occupation, region, employer, or skill—that the dataset does not capture. These gaps create instability and make predictions unreliable. A decision‑maker relying only on this dataset should feel confident about general trends but cautious about cerrtain predictions or subtle subgroup differences. The data is informative, but not complete enough to support conclusions with high rates of precision."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wBmd34qhqqDs"
      }
    }
